educational_summary: A confirmed Kepler transit planet orbiting a distant star; open the NASA link to explore its 3D orbit, size, and host-star info in Eyes on Exoplanets. Kepler found worlds by watching tiny dips in starlight as planets crossed their stars. :contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}

A Kepler-discovered transit planet; use the NASA Eyes page to compare its orbit period and temperature to Jupiter and Earth. The Kepler mission measured star brightness precisely to spot these transits. :contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}
Part of the Kepler-405 system; a confirmed transit planet. Explore the NASA viewer to see multi-planet orbits and relative sizes side-by-side. :contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}

A Kepler transit planet; the NASA Eyes page shows its distance from the star and estimated temperature—handy for explaining why many Kepler worlds are “hot” compared to Jupiter. :contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}
Confirmed via the transit method; use the Eyes controls to view its orbit path and compare with planets in our solar system. :contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}
A confirmed Kepler world shown in NASA Eyes; great example to demonstrate how repeated transit “dips” reveal orbit period. :contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}
A Kepler transit planet; the NASA Eyes page lets you toggle labels to see stellar properties (temperature, radius) that shape the planet’s climate. :contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}
A “hot Jupiter” famous for being the first exoplanet with a mapped cloud pattern; it’s puffier and lower-density than Jupiter and orbits in ~4.9 days. :contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}
A Kepler transit planet; explore its star–planet scale and orbit speed in the NASA Eyes 3D scene to see why many Kepler finds are short-period. :contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}
Confirmed by Kepler using the transit method; the NASA viewer shows how orbital radius and star temperature combine to set equilibrium temperature. :contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}

A hot-Jupiter discovered early in the Kepler mission; it whips around its star in ~3.5 days, making strong, frequent transit signals ideal for teaching the method. :contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}
A confirmed Kepler planet; NASA Eyes lets you compare its radius to Earth/Neptune/Jupiter to classify it visually (rocky vs gas/ice giant). :contentReference[oaicite:11]{index=11}
A Kepler transit world; inspect its orbit period and stellar type in the NASA interface to discuss “year length” beyond our solar system. :contentReference[oaicite:12]{index=12}
A Neptune-like planet (~14 Earth masses) orbiting every ~72 days; use it to contrast “warm Neptunes” with hot Jupiters in classroom demos. :contentReference[oaicite:13]{index=13}
Confirmed via transit; the 3D view shows where it sits relative to the star’s habitable zone and how that affects likely temperatures. :contentReference[oaicite:14]{index=14}
Part of a multi-planet Kepler system; the Eyes app helps students see how multiple transiting planets create multiple dip patterns in the light curve. :contentReference[oaicite:15]{index=15}
A compact Kepler system member; use NASA’s 3D tools to compare orbits and discuss how transit timing can hint at additional planets. :contentReference[oaicite:16]{index=16}
A confirmed transit planet; open the link to inspect stellar temperature and radius, which drive the planet’s estimated equilibrium temperature. :contentReference[oaicite:17]{index=17}
A Kepler transit discovery; shows how even short descriptions (radius, period) can reveal if a world is likely rocky or gaseous. :contentReference[oaicite:18]{index=18}
A confirmed member of a multi-planet system; great for demonstrating resonance ideas and how multiple “dips” reveal multiple planets. :contentReference[oaicite:19]{index=19}
A confirmed Kepler world; the Eyes panel surfaces discovery method (transit), orbit size, and temperature—perfect for quick explainer cards. :contentReference[oaicite:20]{index=20}
Confirmed via transits; compare its orbit to Earth’s year to understand “short-year” exoplanets common in Kepler data. :contentReference[oaicite:21]{index=21}
A Kepler transit planet; the NASA Eyes interface provides interactive comparisons of size and star type for quick classroom visuals. :contentReference[oaicite:22]{index=22}
Confirmed Kepler planet; good example for discussing how candidates become confirmed as more observations refine the signal. :contentReference[oaicite:23]{index=23}
A transit-confirmed planet; explore its semi-major axis and host-star heat to reason about likely atmospheric conditions. :contentReference[oaicite:24]{index=24}
Kepler transit planet; try overlaying the habitable-zone band in NASA Eyes to show why many Kepler finds sit well inside it. :contentReference[oaicite:25]{index=25}
A compact multi-planet system member; a neat case for illustrating how transit timing variations can reveal gravitational tugs. :contentReference[oaicite:26]{index=26}
A Kepler transit discovery; use NASA Eyes to compare stellar type and luminosity—key to estimating a planet’s equilibrium temperature. :contentReference[oaicite:27]{index=27}
A confirmed Kepler world; shows how even brief transits can signal big, close-in planets with short “years.” :contentReference[oaicite:28]{index=28}
One of several planets in the Kepler-23 system; NASA’s archive lists multiple worlds here—great for discussing system architecture and stability. :contentReference[oaicite:29]{index=29}
